Chapter 2: Descriptive Multivariate Statistics¶

Univariate vs. Multivariate Analysis¶

  • Univariate: a single variable.
  • Multivariate: multiple variables.

Descriptive Statistics Overview¶

Descriptive statistics summarize and describe the main features of a dataset. They can be divided into:

  1. Numerical descriptions – values that capture the center, spread, and shape of the data.
  2. Graphical descriptions – visualizations that reveal distribution, patterns, and outliers.

Numerical Description¶

Measures of Center¶

  • Mean (average)
  • Median (middle value)
  • Mode (most frequent value)
  • Trimmed Mean (mean after removing extremes)

R code: mean(x), median(x), ...

Measures of Spread¶

These describe how spread out the data values are:

  • Variance (var) – average squared deviation from the mean
  • Standard Deviation (sd) – square root of the variance
  • Interquartile Range (IQR) – range of the middle 50% of data
  • Range – difference between maximum and minimum values

R code examples: var(x), sd(x), IQR(x), ...

Other Measures of Distribution Shape¶

Beyond center and spread, we often examine shape:

  • Skewness – measures asymmetry of the distribution

    • Positive skew: long right tail
    • Negative skew: long left tail

  • Kurtosis – measures heaviness of tails compared to a normal distribution

    • High kurtosis: more outliers (heavy tails)
    • Low kurtosis: fewer outliers (light tails)

Graphical Description¶

Visualizations provide intuitive insights into the distribution, variability, and patterns in data:

  • Histogram – shows the distribution’s shape and modality
  • Boxplot – highlights spread, median, and outliers
  • Density Plot – smooth estimate of distribution
  • Scatterplot – explores relationships between two variables

Summary¶

Descriptive statistics combine numerical measures (center, spread, shape) and graphical tools (histogram, boxplot, density plot, scatterplot) to give a comprehensive understanding of a dataset.

2.1 Linear Transformation¶

A linear transformation from variable $x$ to variable $y$ is given by:

$$ y = a + b x $$

where $a$ and $b$ are constants.

Effect on Mean and Standard Deviation¶

  • The mean of $y$ is equal to $a$ plus $b$ times the mean of $x$:
    $$ \mu_y = a + b \mu_x $$

  • The standard deviation of $y$ is equal to the absolute value of $b$ times the standard deviation of $x$:
    $$ \sigma_y = |b| \, \sigma_x $$

Example: Celsius to Fahrenheit¶

Temperature conversion formula:

$$ \text{Fahrenheit} = \tfrac{9}{5} \times \text{Celsius} + 32 $$

Suppose we have 20 temperature values in Celsius with:

  • Mean = 10°C
  • Standard Deviation = 5°C

Convert to Fahrenheit:

  • The mean in Fahrenheit is:
    $$ \mu_F = \tfrac{9}{5} \times 10 + 32 = 50 $$

  • The standard deviation in Fahrenheit is:
    $$ \sigma_F = \tfrac{9}{5} \times 5 = 9 $$

Result:
The mean temperature in Fahrenheit is 50°F, and the standard deviation is 9°F.

2.2 Graphical Description of Univariate Data¶

Graphs help us visualize the distribution of a single variable. The type of graph depends on whether the data is quantitative or qualitative.

Quantitative Data¶

Used for numerical variables (e.g., height, weight, temperature).

Common plots:

  • Histogram – shows frequency distribution
  • Density Curve – smooth estimate of distribution
  • Boxplot – highlights median, spread, and outliers

Qualitative Data¶

Used for categorical variables (in R, these are often stored as factors).

Common plots:

  • Bar Chart – shows counts or proportions for each category
  • Pie Chart – shows relative proportions in a circle format

2.3 Numerical Description of Multivariate Data¶

Measures of Center¶

For multivariate data with $p$ variables, the measure of center is the mean vector:

$$ \bar{\mathbf{x}} = (\bar{x}_1, \bar{x}_2, \cdots, \bar{x}_p)^T $$

Measures of Spread: Variance and Covariance¶

  • For a single variable, variance measures variability.

  • For multiple variables, the generalization of variance is the covariance matrix.

  • A vector is a one-dimensional array.

  • A matrix is a two-dimensional array.

  • A tensor is a multi-dimensional array.

Covariance measures how much two random variables vary together.

Data Matrix¶

A dataset with $n$ observations (rows) and $m$ variables (columns) can be represented as:

$$ \text{Data Matrix:} \quad \begin{bmatrix} x_{11} & x_{12} & \dots & x_{1m} \\ x_{21} & x_{22} & \dots & x_{2m} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \dots & x_{nm} \\ \end{bmatrix} $$

The mean vector is:

$$ \bar{X} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} X_i = (\bar{x}_1, \bar{x}_2, \cdots, \bar{x}_m) $$

Covariance Matrix¶

The sample covariance matrix is:

$$ S = \frac{1}{n-1} \begin{bmatrix} s_{1}^2 & s_{12} & \dots & s_{1m} \\ s_{21} & s_{2}^2 & \dots & s_{2m} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ s_{m1} & s_{m2} & \dots & s_{m}^2 \\ \end{bmatrix} $$

where each covariance term is defined as:

$$ s_{ij} = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{k=1}^{n} (x_{ki} - \bar{x}_i)(x_{kj} - \bar{x}_j) $$

Scaling and Normalization¶

  • Scaling: Rescale data (e.g., test scores) to a fixed range, such as 0–1.
  • Normalization (Z-score):
    $$ z = \frac{\text{data value} - \text{mean}}{\text{standard deviation}} $$

Correlation Matrix¶

A correlation matrix shows correlation coefficients between variables.
Correlation is defined as the covariance of standardized data.

  • Sample correlation coefficient between variables $x$ and $y$:
$$ r_{ij} = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{k=1}^{n} \frac{(x_{ki} - \bar{x}_i)(x_{kj} - \bar{x}_j)}{s_i s_j} $$
  • The sample correlation matrix is:
$$ \Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & r_{12} & \dots & r_{1m} \\ r_{21} & 1 & \dots & r_{2m} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ r_{m1} & r_{m2} & \dots & 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} $$

Comments on Correlation¶

  • Correlation $r$ always satisfies $-1 \le r \le 1$.
  • Extreme values $r = -1$ or $r = 1$ occur when all points lie exactly on a straight line.
  • The correlation coefficient $r$ measures only linear relationships between two quantitative variables.
  • Correlation does not capture curved (nonlinear) relationships, even if they are strong.

Interpretation of Correlation¶

  • If there is a strong positive linear relationship between two variables, the correlation $r$ is close to +1.
  • If there is a strong negative linear relationship, the correlation $r$ is close to -1.
  • If two variables have a weak or no association, the correlation $r$ is close to 0.

Examples¶

  • $r = 0.90$: strong positive linear relationship
  • $r = -0.96$: strong negative linear relationship
  • $r = 0.30$: weak positive linear relationship
  • $r = -0.05$: essentially no linear relationship

Sensitivity to Outliers¶

Like the mean and standard deviation, the linear correlation coefficient is sensitive to outliers and extreme values, which can distort the correlation measure.

Important Notes¶

  • The correlation coefficient $r$ measures only the strength of linear relationships.
  • Correlation does not capture nonlinear associations.
  • Both the covariance matrix and the correlation matrix are always semi–positive definite.

Graphical tools for multivariate data¶

  1. Chernoff faces:

Chernoff faces is to present multivariate variables simultaneously by mapping elements of the human face, such as ears, hair, eyes, and nose, according to numerical values in a dataset. The underlying idea is that since we are adept at interpreting facial expressions in everyday life, we should likewise be capable of discerning subtle variations when they correspond to data points.

Package aplpack

  1. Star plots

Star plots (Chambers, et al., 1983, pp. 158-162) are a useful way to display multivariate observations with an arbitrary number of variables. Each observation is represented as a star-shaped figure with one ray for each variable. For a given observation, the length of each ray is made proportional to the size of that variable. Star plots differ from glyph plots in that all variables are used to construct the plotted star figure; there is no separation into foreground and background variables.

  1. Profile plots or Parallel Coordinate Plots

Profile plots or Parallel Coordinate Plots¶

A parallel coordinate plot illustrates each row in a dataset as a line or profile, with each feature of a row represented by a point on the line. Although parallel coordinate plots may resemble line charts, their approach to translating data into a plot differs significantly. This visualization technique is well-suited for representing multivariate, quantitative data, making it ideal for comparing numerous variables and discerning the relationships among them.

Multivariate skewness and kurtosis¶

The univariate version:

The variance of a random variable: $$E(X - EX)^2$$

The sample variance $$ s^2 = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum (x_i - \bar {x} )^2$$

Skewness is related to 3 rd momement of a random variable population skewness is related to $$EX^3$$.

The sample skewness: $$\frac{1}{n} \sum (x_i - \bar {x} )^3/s^3$$

kurtosis is related to 4th moment of a random variable

The sample kurtosis (different versions exist): $$\frac{1}{n} \sum (x_i - \bar {x} )^4/s^4 - 3 $$

The skewness is around zero, if a distribution is symmetric about the mean. a positive skewness indicates that the distribution is skewed to the right.
A negative skewness indicates that the distribution is skewed to the left.

Kurtosis measures how peaked the distribution is. The kurtosis of a normal distribution is 0. Kurtosis characterizes the relative peakedness or flatness of a distribution compared to the normal distribution. If kurtosis is above zero, the tail of the distribution is longer than a normal distribution. If kurtosis is belwo zero, the tail of the distribution is shorter than a normal distribution.

The multivariate version:

Population Multivariate skewness and Kurtosis:

$$ \beta_{1,p} = E[(\mathbf{x}- \mathbf{\mu})^T \mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1} (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{\mu})]^3 $$

$$ \beta_{2,p} = E[(\mathbf{x}- \mathbf{\mu})^T \mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1} (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{\mu})]^2 $$

The sample skewness and kurtosis:

For a sample of size n, $$ \hat{\beta}_{1,p} = \frac{1}{n^2}\sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^n \left [(\mathbf{x}_i - \bar{\mathbf{x}})^T \mathbf{S}^{-1} (\mathbf{x}_j - \bar{\mathbf{x}}) \right ]^{3} $$

$$ \hat{\beta}_{2,p} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left [(\mathbf{x}_i - \bar{\mathbf{x}})^T \mathbf{S}^{-1} (\mathbf{x}_i - \bar{\mathbf{x}}) \right ]^2 $$

In different statistical packages, they may use different formula for calcualtion. The results may be slightly different. Multivariate skewness and kurtosis measure the same shape characteristics as in the univariate case. However, instead of making the comparison of the distribution of one variable against a univariate normal distribution, they are comparing the joint distribution of several variables against a multivariate normal distribution.

  1. Calculation

  2. The information from the results
